e foods. In a Maya village in Yucatán, cochinita de pibil is made with the native peccary instead of pig. In Mexico City, a savory chile poblano is wrapped in puff-pastry. On Oaxaca’s coast, families of African heritage share their way of cooking the local seafood. The book includes a range of recipes, from the delectably familiar to the intriguingly unusual.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCooking, Mexican. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aamerican history.  abooks for food lovers.  abooks for history lovers.  acoffee table books.  acookbook.  acooking.  aeasy to read.  aeducational books.  aengaging.  aeuropean history.  aevolution of food.  afood and wine.  afood cultures.  afood studies.  afoodies.  agastronomy history.  agifts for friends.  agifts for mom.  ahistory of food.  ahome cooks.  ainteresting food dishes.  alearning while reading.  amexican cookbook.  amexican cuisine.  amexican culture.  amexican dishes.  amexican history.  apolitics and food.  arecipes to try during quarantine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095416840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954168/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY